<DOC><DOCNO> AP890227-0191 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 2130EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     02-27 0398</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0407</SECOND><HEAD>Heavy Snow In North Carolina Mountains</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   More than a foot of snow fell in North Carolina on Monday as wetweather prevailed from the lower Mississippi Valley to Virginia andthe Carolinas.   Dry weather prevailed across the rest of the nation, with clearskies over the Florida Peninsula, much of new england and much ofthe Southwest.   The snowstorm stretching from eastern Kentucky and easternTennessee to the middle Atlantic Coast left 14 inches of new snow onMount Mitchell in North Carolina, leaving a total of 21 inches onthe ground.   A winter storm warning remained in effect for the mountains ofwestern North Carolina, and snow advisories were posted forsoutheastern Kentucky, southern West Virginia, southwesternTennessee, most of Virginia, southern Maryland and southern Delaware.   Light snow fell in the northern Rockies, northern Plains and theupper Mississippi Valley. Redwood Falls, Minn., received 3 inches ofsnow by Monday evening.   In six hours ending at 7 p.m. EST, 2 inches of snow fell atFargo, N.D., and an inch fell at Binghamton, N.Y.; Great Falls andMissoula, Mont., and Nashville, Tenn.   A snow advisory was in effect for central and southeasternMinnesota, and a a blowing snow advisory was issued for westernsections of the state. Advisories for snow and blowing snow wasposted for eastern North Dakota and northwestern Montana. The restof western Montana and much of central Montana were under a snowadvisory.   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 6degrees at Detroit Lakes and Roseau, Minn., to 89 degrees atThermal, Calif.   The forecast for Tuesday called for snow in the northern Rockiesand the northern High Plains and across much of the Great Lakes andOhio Valley; rain prevailing from the lower Mississippi Valley tothe Carolinas and the Middle Atlantic States and over the PacificNorthwest; and fair to partly sunny skies prevailing in the rest ofthe nation.   Temperatures were expected to remain below freezing from thenorthern Rockies to Nebraska and the Dakotas and in northern NewEngland, with highs in the teens from Montana to Minnesota andnorthwest Michigan; above 50 degrees from California to much ofTexas and the southern Atlantic Coast; and in the 70s and lower 80sfrom Southern California to the lower Rio Grande Valley of Texas,Florida and southern Georgia.</TEXT></DOC>